    GF_User user;
    ...
    user.modules = gf_modules_new("/data/gpac/modules", user.config);

    GF_MODULE_LOAD_STATIC(user.modules, audio_filter);
    GF_MODULE_LOAD_STATIC(user.modules, aac_in);
    GF_MODULE_LOAD_STATIC(user.modules, ffmpeg);
    GF_MODULE_LOAD_STATIC(user.modules, mpd_in);
    GF_MODULE_LOAD_STATIC(user.modules, isom);
    GF_MODULE_LOAD_STATIC(user.modules, mpegts_in);
    GF_MODULE_LOAD_STATIC(user.modules, soft_raster);
    GF_MODULE_LOAD_STATIC(user.modules, droid_vidgl);
    GF_MODULE_LOAD_STATIC(user.modules, droid_audio);
    gf_modules_refresh(user.modules);
   ...
}
```

The main issue with the way `strcmp` is used in a lot of the source is that it not only returns a 0 or a negative value, but also positive values (which map to `true`!) if the string differs, consider:

``` c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

int main ()
{
  char str1[] = "video/mp4";
  char str2[] = "video/mp2t";
  int ret = strcmp(str1, str2);

  if (!ret) {
    printf("Not equal\n" );
  } else {
    printf("Equal\n" );
  }

  printf("Exact value of ret is: %d\n", ret );

  return 0;
}
```

This will print "Equal" even though the strings are obviously not equal (return value is 2). 😬 Therefore, I think it should be an explicit test against 0:

`if (ret != 0)`

